div.p:
Now, therefore, my deareſt Miſs Howe, let me repeat my earneſt requeſt (for This is not the firſt time by ſeveral that I have been obliged to chide you on this occaſion),


That you will ſpare my parents, and other relations, in all your converſations about me.—Indeed, I wiſh they had thought fit to take other meaſures with me: But who ſhall judge for them?—The event has juſtified them, and condemned me. They expected nothing good of this vile man; he has not, therefore, deceived them: But they expected other things from me; and I have. And they have the more reaſon to be ſet againſt me, if (as my aunt Hervey wrote formerly See Vol. III. Letter L. p. 248.
                  ) they intended not to force my inclinations, in favour of Mr. Solmes; and if they believe, that my going off was the effect of choice and premeditation.

q.l:
